E-C-S launch types, networking, and scaling.

The same task definition runs under two launch types, and the difference is who owns the host. With the E-C-2 launch type, you manage E-C-2 instances, yourself or with an Auto Scaling Group. You choose the instance type and A-M-I, you can S-S-H in, you pay per instance-hour so idle costs money, and you patch the fleet. With the Fargate launch type, AWS owns the host; it's invisible, there's no maintenance, and you're billed per task v-C-P-U and memory per second, with no idle cost. Fargate uses discrete v-C-P-U and memory pairs, from a quarter-v-C-P-U with half a gig, up to sixteen v-C-P-U with a hundred twenty gigs. The rule of thumb: start with Fargate for simplicity, and move to the E-C-2 launch type with Savings Plans once utilisation is steady and per-hour beats per-second.

For networking, the answer is almost always awsvpc mode, where each task gets its own E-N-I, private I-P, and security group in your V-P-C. Treat tasks like small E-C-2 instances on the network; it's also required for Fargate. The legacy bridge and host modes are E-C-2-only. You attach the service to an A-L-B or N-L-B target group, and E-C-S auto-registers tasks on launch and deregisters them on stop.

Scaling uses Application Auto Scaling, the same engine that scales DynamoDB and Aurora, with target tracking, step, and scheduled policies. For the E-C-2 launch type, you must also scale the underlying instances, and an E-C-S Capacity Provider backed by an Auto Scaling Group does that automatically. Fargate has no underlying capacity to manage, which is much of its appeal.
